Vite Integration
****************

.[perex]
Nette Assets provides seamless integration with Vite, the modern frontend build tool. Get automatic asset bundling, hot module replacement in development, and optimized production builds with zero configuration hassle.

Vite has revolutionized frontend development with its lightning-fast dev server and sophisticated build optimization. Nette Assets brings this power directly into your PHP application with the specialized `ViteMapper` that handles both development and production modes automatically.

.[note]
You need Vite installed and configured in your project. This integration requires Vite's manifest feature to be enabled.


Why Use Vite with Nette?
========================

Modern web applications often require sophisticated asset processing - TypeScript compilation, CSS preprocessing, module bundling, code splitting, and more. Vite excels at all of this while providing:

**Lightning-fast development** - Hot module replacement means your changes appear instantly in the browser without page reloads.

**Optimized production builds** - Automatic code splitting, tree shaking, and asset optimization for maximum performance.

**Zero configuration complexity** - Nette Assets handles the bridge between Vite's build system and your PHP templates automatically.

**Seamless asset references** - Write `{asset 'vite:src/main.js'}` in your template and get complete dependency management.


Basic Setup
===========

First, enable Vite's build manifest in your `vite.config.js`:

```js
// vite.config.js
export default {
	build: {
		manifest: true  // Required for Nette Assets integration
	}
}
```

Then configure the ViteMapper in your Nette configuration:

```neon
# config/common.neon
assets:
	mapping:
		vite:
			type: vite
			path: build    # Where Vite outputs files
```

That's it! Your Vite integration is ready.


Development Mode
================

During development, enable Vite's dev server for the best experience:

```neon
assets:
	mapping:
		vite:
			type: vite
			path: build
			devServer: yes  # Enables development mode
```

When `devServer` is enabled and your application runs in debug mode, Nette Assets automatically connects to Vite's dev server (typically running on `localhost:5173`).

You can also specify a custom dev server URL:

```neon
assets:
	mapping:
		vite:
			type: vite
			path: build
			devServer: https://localhost:3000
```

**Development mode features:**
- Hot module replacement (HMR) - see changes instantly
- Fast builds - no file writing to disk
- Source maps for perfect debugging
- Automatic browser refresh when needed


Production Mode
===============

In production, Vite generates optimized bundles with hashed filenames. Nette Assets reads the manifest file to map your source files to the actual built files:

```latte
{* In development: loads from dev server with HMR *}
{* In production: loads optimized bundle with cache-busting hash *}
{asset 'vite:src/main.js'}
```

Production output example:
```html
<script src="/build/assets/main-4a8f9c7.js" type="module" crossorigin></script>
<link rel="stylesheet" href="/build/assets/main-2b9c8d7.css" crossorigin>
```

The ViteMapper automatically handles:
- Hashed filenames for optimal caching
- Cross-origin attributes for security
- Module type detection
- CSS extraction and linking


Entry Points and Dependencies
=============================

Modern JavaScript applications often split code into multiple files. An "entry point" is your main file that imports other modules, CSS, and assets.

Example entry point `src/main.js`:
```js
import './style.css'
import { createApp } from 'vue'
import App from './App.vue'

createApp(App).mount('#app')
```

When you reference this entry point in your template:

```latte
{asset 'vite:src/main.js'}
```

Nette Assets automatically generates all necessary HTML tags:

```html
<!-- Main JavaScript bundle -->
<script src="/build/assets/main-4a8f9c7.js" type="module" crossorigin></script>

<!-- Extracted CSS -->
<link rel="stylesheet" href="/build/assets/main-2b9c8d7.css" crossorigin>

<!-- Vendor chunks (if any) preloaded for performance -->
<link rel="modulepreload" href="/build/assets/vendor-8c7fa9b.js" crossorigin>
```

All dependencies are handled automatically - you write one line, get complete asset management.


Working with Public Files
=========================

Files in Vite's `public/` directory aren't processed by Vite but are copied as-is to the output. The ViteMapper handles these seamlessly:

```latte
{* References a file from public/ directory *}
{asset 'vite:favicon.ico'}

{* Also works with nested paths *}
{asset 'vite:images/logo.png'}
```

For public files, you can use FilesystemMapper features like automatic extension detection:

```neon
assets:
	mapping:
		vite:
			type: vite
			path: build
			extension: [webp, jpg, png]  # Try WebP first, fallback to JPG/PNG
			versioning: true             # Add cache-busting parameters
```


Practical Examples
==================

**Loading application entry point:**
```latte
{* Single line loads everything your app needs *}
{asset 'vite:src/main.js'}
```

**Multiple entry points:**
```latte
{* Main application *}
{asset 'vite:src/main.js'}

{* Admin panel (separate bundle) *}
{asset 'vite:src/admin.js'}
```

**Conditional loading:**
```latte
{if $user->isAdmin()}
	{asset 'vite:src/admin.js'}
{/if}
```

**Mixed with other assets:**
```latte
{* Traditional CSS first *}
{asset 'styles/legacy.css'}

{* Then modern Vite bundle *}
{asset 'vite:src/main.js'}
```


Configuration Options
=====================

Complete configuration reference:

```neon
assets:
	mapping:
		vite:
			type: vite                    # Required: enables ViteMapper
			path: build                   # Output directory (relative to %wwwDir%)
			url: /assets                  # Custom base URL (optional)
			manifest: .vite/manifest.json # Custom manifest path (optional)
			devServer: yes                # Enable dev server integration
			versioning: true              # Add version params to public files
			extension: [webp, jpg, png]   # Auto-extension for public files
```

**Custom manifest location:**
If your Vite config specifies a custom manifest path:

```js
// vite.config.js
export default {
	build: {
		manifest: 'assets-manifest.json'
	}
}
```

Update your Nette configuration accordingly:

```neon
assets:
	mapping:
		vite:
			type: vite
			path: build
			manifest: build/assets-manifest.json
```


Best Practices
==============

**Use meaningful entry point names:**
```
src/main.js      # Main application
src/admin.js     # Admin interface
src/public.js    # Public pages
```

**Leverage code splitting:**
```js
// Dynamic imports create separate chunks automatically
if (userIsAdmin) {
	import('./admin-features.js').then(module => {
		module.init()
	})
}
```

**Organize by functionality:**
```
src/
├── main.js           # Main entry
├── styles/           # CSS files
├── components/       # Reusable components
└── pages/           # Page-specific code
```

**Consider preloading critical chunks:**
```latte
{* Preload important dynamic imports *}
{preload 'vite:src/critical-feature.js'}
```

The ViteMapper makes modern frontend development in Nette applications effortless. You get all the benefits of Vite's sophisticated build system while maintaining the simplicity of Nette's asset management.
